Date:  23/7/1970
Source:  Dominion
Author:
Vol / Page:  15/1-3
Edition:
Quote:  The news from Britain that hogweed or cow parsnip as it is more commonly called, has been added to the list ... The New Zealand Weed and Pest Control society in recent publication `Standard common Names For weeds in New Zealands' records the name cow parsnip without giving the specific name. This plant could be H. sphondlylium a native of the British isle and at one time widely advocated as a suitable stock food because of its thick fleshy tap root. Hogweed in New Zealand is a popular descriptive name for four different weeds. Two of these, namely the twin cress and wart cress, belong to the same genus. The other two are the wild portulaca and wire weed, which are in no way related. The popular names of the latter illustrate how confusing the use of names like fire weed or wandering willie can be as a means of identifying weeds and plants. These common names of plants frequently have only local significance and in cases may even become obsolete. For this reason botanical names are ...
